# Question

Are we able to determine pieces of a PDF that depend only on an observable? In some HistFactory code, it was learned by experience that

```c++
  RooMinimizer minim(*nll);
  minim.setStrategy( _minStrat );
  minim.setPrintLevel( _printLevel-1 );
  minim.setProfile(); /* print out time */
  minim.setEps( _minTolerance / 0.001 );
  minim.setOffsetting( _nllOffset );
  if (_optConst > 0) minim.optimizeConst( _optConst );
```

the last line here provided some speed up in some cases. This particular speed up can be traced to these lines in RooFit: https://root.cern.ch/doc/master/RooAbsOptTestStatistic_8cxx_source.html#l00499

```c++
   case Activate:     
     cxcoutI(Optimization) << "RooAbsOptTestStatistic::constOptimize(" << GetName() 
            << ") optimizing evaluation of test statistic by finding all nodes in p.d.f that depend exclusively"
            << " on observables and constant parameters and precalculating their values" << endl ;
     optimizeConstantTerms(kTRUE,doAlsoTrackingOpt) ;
     break ;
```

which seems to indicate that it optimizes the calculation of the test statistic by finding all nodes in the pdf that depend only on observables and constant parameters and precalculating the values. I can only imagine this happens in the case of a variation that is small and is determined to have negligible impact somehow.

